50|$|The owners, {{agents and}} masters of vessels loading in the United States of America are {{forbidden}} by {{an act of}} Congress, commonly called the Harter Act, passed in the year 1893, to insert in their contracts of affreightment any clause exempting the shipowner from <b>liability</b> <b>for</b> the <b>negligence</b> of his servants; but it {{is at the same time}} enacted that, provided all reasonable skill and care has been exercised by the shipowner to make the vessel seaworthy and fit for the voyage at its commencement, the shipowner shall not be liable for any loss caused by the negligence of the master or crew in the navigation of the vessel, or by perils of the sea or certain other causes set forth in the act.|$|R
